  "slug": "meatloaf",
  "title": "Meatloaf",
  "subtitle": "Glazed beef-and-pork loaf for Sunday night.",
  "excerpt": "Beef and pork mince bound with soaked bread and onion, baked in a tin under a glossy ketchup glaze. The American Sunday-night dinner. Slices cleanly for sandwiches the next day.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Fannie Farmer, Boston Cooking-School Cook Book (1896 onwards, public domain) gives the early American meatloaf canon. The ketchup-glaze tradition emerged in the depression-era 1930s and was canonised in the WPA state-cookery surveys.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Half beef, half pork. Soaked bread instead of breadcrumbs from a packet, so the loaf stays tender. Onion softened in butter before it goes in, so it isn't crunchy. The mixture pressed into a tin, brushed with a sweet tangy glaze, and baked for an hour at 180°C.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The loaf needs to rest in the tin for 10 minutes before turning out. Cut too soon and it crumbles.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
